        "explanation": "Oral hypoesthesia (numbness/tingling of the tongue and oral mucosa) is a unique side effect of sublingual asenapine, occurring in ~5–7% of patients. It is usually transient and not harmful, but is important to distinguish from oromandibular dystonia, which involves involuntary movement."
